06225nam a22010215i 9783110651331DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20222022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831106513317 a10.1515/97831106513312doi  a(DE-B1597)514472  a(OCoLC)1306540708  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a491.800aDiachronic Slavonic Syntax :bTraces of Latin, Greek and Church Slavonic in Slavonic Syntax /ced. by Sandra Birzer, Imke Mendoza. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (X, 305 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTrends in Linguistics. Studies and Monographs [TiLSM] ,x1861-4302 ;v3480 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe impact of the ecclesiastical languages Greek, Latin and Church Slavonic on the Slavic standard languages still lacks a systematic analysis in the theoretical framework of contact linguistics. Based on corpus data, this volume offers an account in the light of “literacy language contact”, i.e. contact between varieties that are used only in a written variant and only in formal registers. Latin was used as literary language in medieval Slavia Romana; Greek was the source language for Church Slavonic, which, in turn, was the literary language for many Slavonic speaking communities and thus had an enormous impact on the development of the modern Slavonic standard languages. The book offers in-depth analyses of the impact of Latin on pre-Standard Slavonic varieties, the influence of Greek on (Old) Church Slavonic and the role of Church Slavonic as a source language for Old and Modern Russian. The contributions discuss (morpho)syntactic phenomena such as non-finite clauses, relative clauses, word order, the use and function of case and tense forms. The volume addresses Slavists, General linguists and scholars of Classical Philology interested in language contact and syntactic issues.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 4aAltkirchenslavisch. 4aMorphosyntax. 4aSlavische Sprachen. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aClassical Languages.  aHistorical (Morpho)Syntax.  aLanguage Contact.  aSlavonic Languages.1 aBirzer, Sandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBirzer, Sandra, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDekker, Simeon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEberle, Marisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEckhoff, Hanne Martine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFuchsbauer, Jürgen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGavrančić, Sanja Perić, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKisiel, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKosek, Pavel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMendoza, Imke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMendoza, Imke, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNavrátilová, Olga, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPichkhadze, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSobotka, Piotr, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSonnenhauser, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSłoboda, Agnieszka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTomelleri, Vittorio S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aČech, Radek, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aŠimić,